SIMPLE: revelation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Revelation
<hw>Rev`e*la"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>r⟦eacute⟧v⟦eacute⟧lation</ets>, L. <ets>revelatio</ets>. See
<er>Reveal</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of revealing,
disclosing, or discovering to others what was before unknown to
them.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is revealed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Theol.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>The act of
revealing divine truth.</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>That which is revealed
by God to man; esp., the Bible.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By <qex>revelation</qex> he made known unto me the mystery, as I
wrote afore in few words.</q> <rj><qau>Eph. iii. 3.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Specifically, the last book of the sacred canon,
containing the prophecies of <person>St. John</person>; the
<altname>Apocalypse</altname> or <altname>Book of Revelation</altname>
or <altname>The Revelation of Saint John</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Revelator</ent>⟦br⟧
